# Directional Light

Directional light simulates distant sunlight — parallel rays with no distance falloff.

```
const sun = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 1.4);
sun.position.set(5, 8, 4);
ctx.add(sun);
```

The position sets direction only — distance from the origin has no effect. Only the angle matters.

## Shadow Maps

Enable shadows with:

```
ctx.renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true;
sun.castShadow = true;
mesh.castShadow = true;
mesh.receiveShadow = true;
```

# Point Light

Point lights emit in all directions from a single position, with realistic falloff.

```
const lamp = ctx.point(
  0xff8844,  // warm orange
  2.0,       // intensity
  12,        // max distance (0 = infinite)
  2          // decay exponent
);
lamp.position.set(0, 3, 0);
ctx.add(lamp);
```

Decay of 2 gives physically accurate inverse-square falloff.

Animate the position in update() to create orbiting flames, moving lamps, or flickering effects:

```
export function update(ctx, dt) {
  const t = ctx.elapsed;
  lamp.position.x = Math.sin(t) * 5;
  lamp.position.z = Math.cos(t) * 5;
}
```

# Three-Point Studio Lighting

Classic photography lighting with three directional lights:

```
// Key — primary illumination
const key = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xfff0cc, 1.4);
key.position.set(5, 8, 4);

// Fill — softens key-side shadows
const fill = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0x4488ff, 0.5);
fill.position.set(-5, 3, 2);

// Rim — separates subject from background
const rim = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xff4488, 0.7);
rim.position.set(0, -2, -8);
```

This rig produces a well-defined professional look used in product renders and character animation. The colored fill and rim add depth without requiring HDR environment maps.

# Hemisphere Light

Hemisphere light simulates outdoor sky/ground bounce — sky color from above, ground color reflected from below.

```
const hemi = ctx.hemi(
  0x8888ff,  // sky color (blue)
  0x664422,  // ground color (warm brown)
  1.2        // intensity
);
ctx.add(hemi);
```

Ideal for outdoor scenes. It produces soft, natural illumination without the harshness of directional lights, and is cheap to compute — no shadow maps required.

Combine with a single low-intensity directional light to add just enough directionality for material PBR to read clearly.
